Pour the @water{300%ml}(for the rice) into a #medium saucepan{} with a tight-fitting #lid{}.

Stir in the @saffron{1%sachet}, @basmati rice{150%g} and @salt{1/4%tsp} and bring to the boil.
Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the lid.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, halve the @bell pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Slice into thin strips.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #large frying pan{} on high heat.
Once hot, add the sliced pepper and fry until just soft, ~{5-6%minutes}. Continue to stir while it cooks.

Add the @king prawns{150%g} and @diced chorizo{60%g} to the pan and fry until the prawns are cooked through, ~{4-5%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw prawns. They're cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).
Cut the @lemon{1} into wedges.

Once the chorizo has browned, reduce the heat to medium and add the garlic, @tomato puree{30%g} and @Central American style spice mix{1%sachet}. Cook, stirring, for ~{1%minute}.

Stir the @chicken stock paste{15%g}, @honey{1%tbsp} and @water{100%ml}(for the sauce) into the #frying pan{}.

Bring to the boil, then lower the heat and simmer until the sauce is thickened, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Once the saffron rice is cooked, fluff it up with a #fork{} and gently stir it into the sauce.

Stir through the @peas{120%g}, @sun-dried tomato paste{25%g} and a good squeeze of lemon juice.
Taste and add more salt and pepper or lemon juice if needed.

Share the spiced prawn and chorizo rice between your #bowls{}.

Serve with a dollop of @creme fraiche{75%g} on top and any remaining lemon wedges on the side.

Enjoy!